Test it:                            

  ./run-kai.sh                                                                  
   
  You'll get a sudo prompt for the firewall setup. Once inside, to verify       
  network restriction is working:                                             

  # should work
  curl -s https://api.anthropic.com >/dev/null && echo ok

  # should be blocked (non-443 port)
  curl -s --max-time 3 http://example.com || echo blocked

  And on the host in a second terminal, to capture what claude actually connects
   to:

  kai-netwatch
  # then run claude inside the container normally


===

A few notes on the design:                                                    
                                                                                
  Interaction with kai-firewall: The REDIRECT fires in the nat PREROUTING table,
   before the FORWARD chain where kai-firewall's DROP rules live. So port 443   
  traffic is intercepted by the proxy regardless of the kai-firewall DROP rule —
   the two don't conflict.                                                      
                                                                                
  Workflow for discovery: Before enforcing, run kai-proxy --discover in one     
  terminal while using claude in the container normally. It logs every domain   
  reached. Add any missing ones to kai-proxy-allowlist.conf, commit, then switch
   to normal enforcing mode.                                                    
                                                                                
  Missing from this pass: kai-proxy isn't yet wired into run-kai.sh because it  
  needs a separate terminal for interactive mode. Worth a deliberate decision   
  about whether to daemonize it or keep it user-facing.

